ces Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States, Agrosphere Institute (ICG-IV), Forschungszentrum Juelich GmbH, 52425 Juelich, Germany; Chong, S.C., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States; Huang, Z., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States, State Key Laboratory of Biocontrol, School of Life Sciences, Sun Yat-sen University, Guangzhou 510275, China; Wu, W., Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA, United States; Gu, B., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States; Jardine, P., Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States; Criddle, C., Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Stanford University, Stanford, CA, United States; Zhou, J., Department of Botany and Microbiology, Institute for Environmental Genomics, University of Oklahoma, Norman, OK, United States, Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN, United States, Department of Botany and Microbiology, Institute for Environmental Genomics, University of Oklahoma, 101 David L. Boren Blvd., Norman, OK 73019, United States","Owing to their vast diversity and as-yet uncultivated status, detection, characterization and quantification of microorganisms in natural settings are very challenging, and linking microbial diversity to ecosystem processes and functions is even more difficult. Microarray-based genomic technology for detecting functional genes and processes has a great promise of overcoming such obstacles. Here, a novel comprehensive microarray, termed GeoChip, has been developed, containing 24 243 oligonucleotide (50 mer) probes and covering > 10 000 genes in > 150 functional groups involved in nitrogen, carbon, sulfur and phosphorus cycling, metal reduction and resistance, and organic contaminant degradation. The developed GeoChip was successfully used for tracking the dynamics of metal-reducing bacteria and associated communities for an in situ bioremediation study. This is the first comprehensive microarray currently available for studying biogeochemical processes and functional activities of microbial communities important to human health, agriculture, energy, global climate change, ecosystem management, and environmental cleanup and restoration. It is particularly useful for providing direct linkages of microbial genes/populations to ecosystem processes and functions. © 2007 International Society for Microbial Ecology All rights reserved.","Bioremediation; Functional genes; Microarray; Microbial community","carbon; metal; nitrogen; phosphorus; sulfate; article; bioremediation; environment; metabolism; methodology; microarray analysis; microbiology; oligonucleotide probe; oxidation reduction reaction; Biodegradation, Environmental; Carbon; Environment; Environmental Microbiology; Metals; Microarray Analysis; Nitrogen; Oligonucleotide Probes; Oxidation-Reduction; Phosphorus; Sulfates; Bacteria (microorganisms)",,"carbon, 7440-44-0; nitrogen, 7727-37-9; phosphorus, 7723-14-0; sulfate, 14808-79-8; Carbon, 7440-44-0; Metals; Nitrogen, 7727-37-9; Oligonucleotide Probes; Phosphorus, 7723-14-0; Sulfates",,,,"Amann, R.I., Ludwig, W., Schleifer, K., Phylogenetic identification and in situ detection of individual microbial cells without cultivation (1995) Microbiol Rev, 59, pp. 143-169; Bodrossy, L., Sessitsch, A., Oligonucleotide microarrays in microbial diagnostics (2004) Curr Opin Microbiol, 7, pp. 245-254; DeRisi, J.L., Iyer, V.R., Brown, P.O., Exploring the metabolic and genetic control of gene expression on a genomic scale (1997) Science, 278, pp. 680-686; Fitter, A.H., Gilligan, C.A., Hollingworth, K., Kleczkowski, A., Twyman, R.M., Pitchford, J.W., Biodiversity and ecosystem function in soil (2005) Funct Ecol, 19, pp. 369-377; Gao, H., Wang, Y., Liu, X., Ya